label("$R$", R, NW);
//label("$S$", S, NE);
label("$T$", T, dir(270));
label("$\alpha$", A, 1.5*dir(70));
label("$\alpha$", B, 1.5*dir(200));
label("$40^\circ$", P, NW);
[/asy]

Then $\angle ABR = \alpha$ and $\angle ABS = \alpha$ for some angle $\alpha,$ so $\angle AOB = 2 \alpha.$  Also, $\angle APB = 40^\circ.$

Let $x = \angle APT.$  Then
\begin{align*}
\angle ATR &= 180^\circ - \angle TRA - \angle ART \\
&= 180^\circ - \angle BTP - \angle AOR \\
&= 180^\circ - x - \alpha,
\end{align*}so
\begin{align*}
\angle ATO &= 180^\circ - \angle ATR - \angle RTO \\
&= 180^\circ - (180^\circ - x - \alpha) - 90^\circ \\
&= 90^\circ - x - \alpha.
\end{align*}Also,
\begin{align*}
\angle APO &= 180^\circ - \angle TPO - \angle APT \\
&= 180^\circ - (180^\circ - \alpha) - x \\
&= \alpha - x.
\end{align*}Since $AOPT$ is cyclic,
\[\angle AOT = \angle APT = x.\]Hence,
\[2 \alpha + 40^\circ = \angle AOB = 2x.\]Also,
\[\angle ATO + \angle APO = \alpha - x + 90^\circ - x - \alpha = -2x + 90^\circ.\]Since $\angle AOT = x,$
\[\angle AOB = \angle AOT + \angle TOB = x + (-2x + 90^\circ) = 90^\circ - x.\]Hence,
\[2 \alpha + 40^\circ = 90^\circ - x.\]Then $2 \alpha = 50^\circ - x.$  But $2 \alpha + 40^\circ = 2x,$ so
\[2x + 40^\circ = 50^\circ - x.\]Solving, we find $x = 10^\circ,$ so $\angle AOB = 90^\circ - x = \boxed{80^\circ}.$

